  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(53) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Thinkest thou that I cannot now pray . . .?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—There is a strange and suggestive blending of the possible and the impossible in these words. Could He have brought Himself to utter that prayer, it would have been answered. But He could not so pray unless He knew it to be in harmony with His Father’s will, and He had been taught, in that hour of agony, that it was not in harmony, and therefore He would not utter it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Presently.—The modern English reader needs to be reminded once more that the word means immediately, without a moment’s delay.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Presently.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The modern English reader needs to be reminded once more that the word means ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "immediately,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " without a moment’s delay.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Twelve legions.—The number is probably suggested by that of the Apostles. Not twelve weak men, one a traitor and the others timorous, but twelve legions of the armies of the Lord of Hosts. Note the Roman word appearing here, as in Mark 5:9; Mark 5:15, as the representative of warlike might.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Twelve",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "legions.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The number is probably suggested by that of the Apostles. Not twelve weak men, one a traitor and the others timorous, but twelve legions of the armies of the Lord of Hosts. Note the Roman word appearing here, as in ",
            "children": []
